## Explaining The Question
This Question is rated **Easy**. Which I think is ***extremely*** inaccurate. I think it is more of a **Medium** question. The question and its description is ***highly misleading ***.

***This is a trick question***. We're told that the node we're given, is the node that we will be deleting. Which is ***wrong***. ***We can never delete the node*** we're given. The reason for this is that we're never given access to the head of the linked list, which maintains the `next` pointer to the node that we're going to delete. 
What this means is we're going to fully break the list if we delete the node we're given.

***So what do we do?***
Given our limitations to deleting the given node, we're instead going to move the values of our nodes backwards. Meaning we're going to shift all the values we have one node back. Then we're going to ***delete the last node*** of the list.

***What? That makes no sense!?***
I know it sounds confusing. But it's really simple. See the example below

Node to delete: `5`
Linked List: `1->2->3->4->5->6->7->8->9`
Note: We can only see `(5->6->7->8->9)` Because we're not given access to the `head`

Now ***let's start shifting the values backwards***:
Cycle 1:
Note: This is where we start, on node `5`. So what we do is Make node `5` become node `6`
What we see `(6->6->7->8->9)`
Linked List: `1->2->3->4->6->6->7->8->9`

Cycle 2:
Note: We've now changed node `5` to become `6` so let's change `6` to become `7`
What we see `(6->7->7->8->9)`
Linked List: `1->2->3->4->6->7->7->8->9`

Cycle 3:
Note: We've now changed node `6` to become `7` so let's change `7` to become `8`
What we see `(6->7->8->8->9)`
Linked List: `1->2->3->4->6->7->8->8->9`

Repeat this until we reach the very last node. 
Once at the last node we should have a linked list like this:
Linked List: `1->2->3->4->6->7->8->9->9`

Now all we have to do, is remove the last duplicate node and we would have effectively deleted the given node.

##  Recommended Knowledge
1. Linked Lists
2. Linked List Traversal
3. Linked List Traversal (Recursively) * ***Not needed but recommened***
4. How to changed linked list values

## What do we know?
1. We have been given a trick question. See above.
2. We need to shift all the given values in the linked list backwards

## How we're going to do it:
1. At each node, we're going to set the current nodes value to whatever the next value is.
2. We will have a prev pointer, keeping track of the last node we visited, which we update at every node
3. Once we have changed all of these values and we have reached the end of the list, we will remove the last node of the list as that is a dupe.

## Big O Notation:
* Time Complexity:   *O(**n**)* | Where ***n*** is the list length | As we will traverse them all
* Space Complexity: *O(**1**)* | As we never allocate extra space

## Leetcode Results:

See Submission Link: 

* Runtime: 63 ms, faster than ***97.49%*** of JavaScript online submissions for Delete Node in a Linked List
* Memory Usage: 44.7 MB, less than ***18.59%*** of JavaScript online submissions for Delete Node in a Linked List

[![LeetCode](https://img.shields.io/badge/LeetCode-000000?style=for-the-badge&logo=LeetCode&logoColor=#d16c06)](https://leetcode.com/submissions/detail/682104375/)


***

# The Solution
var deleteNode = function (node, prev) {

	/* -------------------------------------------------------------------------- */
	/*                      237. Delete Node in a Linked List                     */
	/* -------------------------------------------------------------------------- */

    /**
     * @author  Samuel Hinchliffe
     * @see    {@link linkedin.com/in/samuel-hinchliffe-🚀-2bb5801a5/ | Author's Linkedin }
     * @see    {@link github.com/Samuel-Hinchliffe}
     */

	// NOTE: This is not a easy problem.
	// It would be easy, if this was JUST deleting a node.
	// But as we never have the head of the linked list, this is a trick question.
	// So instead, we shift all the values backwards and remove the last node.

	// We're going to do this recursively, meaning, that we're going to apply the same
	// rules for every node we encounter. So this must mean, we're going to have to prepare
	// ourselves for every outcome possible. Starting with:

	// Does the next node exist?
	// IF NOT: We're at the end of the list, so
	// we nullify the prev node's next pointer. (As that pointer is on the last node)
	// IF the next node does exist:
	if (node.next) {
		// We update our prev node pointer, to be this current node (We do this because we need to always know the previous node)
		// Because we will nullify it's next in the end.
		prev = node;

		// We now set our current nodes value to the next node's value. (Shifting the values)
		// Because we're going to shift all the values backwards. The reason for this is because we cannot just
		// delete the node, as the unaccessible head will still point towards it. (This is what makes this a trick question)
		node.val = node.next.val;

		// Now recursively call this function, with the next node.
		// Keep doing the above until we reach the very end of the list
		deleteNode(node.next, prev);
	} else {
		prev.next = null;
	}

	// Don't worry if you're just starting our on linked lists and don't understand this.
	// Leetcode has marked this as easy, but it's not. They make it look simple, but it's a trick question.
	// If you don't understand, you're all good. It's just a trick question.
};
```

