Note, this post is a modified version of the following post:
https://leetcode.com/problems/delete-node-in-a-linked-list/discuss/65547/My-C%2B%2B-solution-in-1-line 

Note: The tricky point is that we can not use: 
    node=node->next
Because we have not change the address content stored in the previous node.
It just likes that you change your room number but remains everything in the room, isn’t it

In fact , a linked list will be stored like this:

**head ->  {val1,   address2}    {val2, address3}  {val3, address4}   {val4, NULL}**

So, if we are given access to the *cur = {val3, address4}

If we want to delete the *cur, we have to change the content stored in *cur.

If we use cur=cur->next, what happens ?

OOPS ! nothing happens ... because the "address#" stored in the linked list keeps no changing!

So "cur=cur->next" makes no impact on the linked list.

C++
```
class Solution {// BEST1:
public:
    void deleteNode(ListNode* node) {
        *node = *(node->next);
    }
};
```
Explanation:
Recall the definition of ListNode:
```
/**
 * Definition for singly-linked list.
 * struct ListNode {
 *     int val;
 *     ListNode *next;
 *     ListNode(int x) : val(x), next(NULL) {}
 * };
 */
 ```
 Let's imagaing each List Node as something like folllowing in the memory:
 {val, address_to_next}
  So 
  ```
   *node = *(node->next);
   ```
   means you copy EVERYTHING from one (the obejct pointed by node->next) to another (the object pointed by node)
   So its function is the  same as:
   ```
	 node->val = node->next->val;
     node->next = node->next->next; 
```

