```

void deleteNode(ListNode* node) {

        ListNode* temp = node->next;
        node->val = temp->val;
        node->next = temp->next;

        delete temp;
    }
```

**Explanation:**

Since we have the access to the node to be deleted and don't have the access to head node of the list as per the problem description.
So we are doing small trick here to delete the given node.

***Example***: Try to delete 2 from below list.
1->2->3->4->NULL.

Lets consider the node's address start from 100 like this **1(100)->2(101)->3(102)->4(103)->NULL**.

```
//Here we are storing the address of the next node of 2 (to be deleted) to temporary variable (that is node 3).
ListNode* temp = node->next; // temp will have node at address 102.
```

```
//Then storing the value from the next node to current node.
//Now the list will look like "1(100)->3(101)->3(102)->4(103)->NULL"
node->val = temp->val;
```

```
// Now linking the 4th node's address to the second node's next pointer and ignoring the third node("3(102)").
// Now the list will look like "1(100)->3(101)->4(103)->NULL"
node->next = temp->next;
```

```
// Finaly deleting the third node ("3(102)") wich is initially stored in the temp variable.
delete temp;
```

