# Intuition
<!-- Describe your first thoughts on how to solve this problem. -->
Deleting a node in a singly linked list is to manipulate the values and references of the nodes in the list, instead of physically removing the node from memory.
# Approach
<!-- Describe your approach to solving the problem. -->
- Check if the input node is null, if so return as there is nothing to delete.
- If the node is not null, update its value to be the value of its next node and its next reference to be the next reference of its next node.
- This effectively removes the next node and connects the current node to the node after the next node, thus deleting the current node.
# Complexity
- Time complexity:
<!-- Add your time complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->
The time complexity of this function is O(1)
- Space complexity:
<!-- Add your space complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->
The space complexity of this function is O(1)
# Code
```
/**
 * Definition for singly-linked list.
 * function ListNode(val) {
 *     this.val = val;
 *     this.next = null;
 * }
 */
/**
 * @param {ListNode} node
 * @return {void} Do not return anything, modify node in-place instead.
 */
var deleteNode = function(node) {

    if(node ===  null) return;

       else{
           if(node.next!==null){
                node.val = node.next.val;
                node.next =  node.next.next;
           }
       }
};
```

